org.dmd.dmc
Class DmcValue<E>

java.lang.Object
  org.dmd.dmc.DmcValue<E>
Type Parameters:
E - The "primitive" type
All Implemented Interfaces:
java.io.Serializable
public abstract class DmcValue<E>
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.io.Serializable

Just a thought experiment. Why don't we derive all value classes from a common base? The initial concept seems sound, except that you can't get an Iterator over the primitive type easily e.g. Iterator for your DmcTypeString. We're trying to come up with the leanest possible implementation of the attribute. There should be as little overhead for each attribute as possible.

hash

public int hash()
Derived classes must override this method to supply a hash code for their underlying type. This allows any value to be supported in HASHMAPPED or TREEMAPPED attributes. At this level we throw an exception.

Returns:
the hash value of your underlying type or complex type.

getKey

public java.lang.Object getKey()
Derived classes should overload this method to return the Object on which they can be mapped. If you don't override it, this method just returns the value. So, if this were the value for a String, the String itself would be returned as the key.

Returns:
the key used to access this value in a map.
